step_normalize:prompt:model=Claude Sonnet 4 v1;temperature=0;max_tokens=100
##system_prompt:
You are a strict normalizer. From the first word in ${user_input}, identify the keywords below and output exactly ONE of:
"energy" or "cera" or "horizons" or "platts" or "herold" or "corporate" or "mi" or "ratings" or "mobility" or "dji" or "sustainable1"

Mapping rules:
- Strictly accept only these spelling variants: "CORPORATE", "corporate", "ENERGY", "energy", "mi", "MI", "RATINGS", "ratings", "MOBILITY", "mobility", "dji", "DJI", "CERA", "cera", "ENERGY", "energy", "horizons", "HORIZONS", "platts", "PLATTS", "HEROLD", "Herold", "sustainable1", "SUSTAINABLE1"

CRITICAL RULES:
- Strictly only use the first word in ${user_input}
- If the input does not clearly match any of the above mapping rules, output "INVALID".















##user_prompt:
${user_input}

CRITICAL: No preamble, no quotes
----
step_energyCheck:if:("energy"=="${step_normalize_output}") or ("horizons"=="${step_normalize_output}") or ("platts"=="${step_normalize_output}") or ("cera"=="${step_normalize_output}") or ("herold"=="${step_normalize_output}") or ("sustainable1"=="${step_normalize_output}")
----
<step_endCheck:if:("corporate"=="${step_normalize_output}") or ("mi"=="${step_normalize_output}") or ("mobility"=="${step_normalize_output}") or ("dji"=="${step_normalize_output}") or ("ratings"=="${step_normalize_output}")
----

        { image: { path: susredBlackLogo, x: 1.67, y: 6.97, w: 1.57, h: 0.52 } },

        {
            placeholder: {
                options: { name: "slideNumber", type: "sldNum", x: 12.48, y: 7.18, w: 0.34, h: 0.24, fontFace: "Arial", fontSize: 7, color: colors.white, align: "right", valign: "middle" },
                text: "<#>"
            }
        },
        // Disclaimer text
        { text: { text: "${step_disclaimerConfirmed_output}", options: { x: 0.62, y: 0.49, w: 12.10, h: 6.33, fontFace: "Arial", fontSize: 10, color: colors.black, align: "left", valign: "middle", bullet: false, margin: 0 } } },
    ],
});

step_partnerPlan:prompt:model=Claude Sonnet 4 v1;temperature=0;max_tokens=32000;use_chat_history
##system_prompt:
Your job is to create a top-level plan for a powerpoint presentation to be executed on by a team of consultants that work for you. Give instructions to the team on what information they should gather, what messages they should be delivering, a rough sketch of the flow of the presentation you wish to see.

You are working on behalf of the user. <User Request + Content>

Keep in mind these practices:

0. Give a suggestion for the Presentation Title and tell the team to start with a title slide. !!! title slide must be used only as the first slide !!!
You MUST give 10 keywords to describe the presentation title in the presentation notes. This will be used to select an [imageUrl] at another step.
1. Structure the Story First
Think like a consultant: slides are not the story, they‚Äôre evidence. 
Start with the Pyramid Principle (Barbara Minto) State your main message first (‚ÄúSo what?‚Äù). Support with key arguments.
This is crucial: NEVER create, assume or guess any fact, claim or data. NEVER state information without referencing where it came from.
Use a clear storyline:
Executive Summary ‚Üí Context ‚Üí Analysis ‚Üí Implications ‚Üí Recommendations.
Ensure every slide advances the storyline.
2. Use Data Effectively
McKinsey slides are data-dense but scannable:
Charts over tables: Prefer visuals  over raw tables.
Highlight key numbers: Bold, color, or annotate what matters.
3. Design for Decision-Making
The audience is often executives with short attention spans:
Make slides self-sufficient: A reader can grasp the point without narration.
Use annotations: arrows, labels, brief notes to highlight insights.
Keep white space: better to have 30 clean slides than 10 overloaded ones.
4. Tell a Story with the Deck
Structure the full deck like a narrative:
Executive Summary: ‚ÄúHere‚Äôs what‚Äôs happening and why it matters.‚Äù
Context: Situation, market, or background.
Analysis: Key findings, charts, comparisons.
Implications: ‚ÄúSo what does this mean?‚Äù
Recommendations: Clear call to action.
Next Steps: Execution plan.
5. Charts
Only suggest charts if the data is provided in the context. Do not make up data.
6. Source verification
Explicitly list the URLs or links to reliable, credible and verifiable sources for every factual claim, statement and data you have collected so far.
CRUCIAL: You MUST ALWAYS check that these URLs exist and can be accessed by the general public.
7. If the user explicitly uses this keyword: "Update Branding", do not change any of the text, data or any other elements except for logo and disclaimer.

**CRITICAL RULES:**
- When webpage data is used in slide creation, you MUST add all source URLs to the footnote section of each slide. URLs must start with https://
- Add " | Web sources: " followed by the URLs in the footnotes of each slide.
- If there are more than 1 URL, separate them with semicolons.
- Do NOT generate URLs unless they are explicitly provided in ${user_input}
- NEVER create or guess website names, domains or links. Do NOT guess or assume any URL format.
- Every URL must match those given in ${step_extractUrls_output}

**Examples:**
Without URLs: "Source: S&P Global"
With URLs: "Source: S&P Global | Web sources: https://example1.com, https://example2.com"

>step_chartInstructions:data
{ "True" : """## CRITICAL EXECUTION RULES FOR S&P GLOBAL CHART GENERATION

### ABSOLUTE REQUIREMENTS - NO EXCEPTIONS

You must use given data ... do not derive your own data.

#### 1. MANDATORY CODE STRUCTURE
Every response MUST follow this exact pattern:

// 1. CHART POSITIONING (adjustable variables)
const chartPosition_slide<slideNumber> = {
    x: #.#,    // Left margin (adjustable)
    y: #.#,    // Top margin (adjustable) 
    w: #.#,      // Width (adjustable)
    h: #.#       // Height (adjustable)
};

// 2. CHART DATA (properly formatted arrays)
const chartData_slide<slideNumber> = [/* valid data structure */];

Examples:

// 2. CHART DATA (properly formatted arrays)
const chartData_slide2 = [
    {
        name: 'seriesName',
        labels: ["category1", "category2", "category3", "category4", "category5"], // categoryLabels
        values: [3, 1, 4, 1, 5.9] // dataValues
    }
];

// 2. CHART DATA (three series with properly formatted arrays)
const chartData_slide3 = [
    {
        name: 'series1Name',
        labels: ["Q1", "Q2", "Q3", "Q4", "Q5"], // categoryLabels
        values: [1, 5, 25, 120, 230] // dataValues
    },
    {
        name: 'series2Name',
        labels: ["Q1", "Q2", "Q3", "Q4", "Q5"], // categoryLabels
        values: [0, 12, 24, 48, 96] // dataValues
    },
    {
        name: 'series3Name',
        labels: ["Q1", "Q2", "Q3", "Q4", "Q5"], // categoryLabels
        values: [2, 9, 81, 160, 320] // dataValues
    }
];

// 3. CHART SETTINGS (S&P compliant configuration)
const chartOptions = {
    x: chartPosition.x,
    y: chartPosition.y, 
    w: chartPosition.w,
    h: chartPosition.h,
    chartColors: ['006D89', 'DC7900', 'B92051', '501555', '0F9E7A', '00495B', 'C94100', '1D3BAA', 'CD6083', '125E1F', '929497', '782080', '7284CA', '9D5700', 'B280B6', '566CBF', '6CABBB', 'C18B28', '3C9D4D', '6B0F01']
    showLegend: true, // Set true if multiple times series. Set false if single time series
    legendPos: 't', // default legend placement
    legendFontFace: 'Arial',
    legendFontSize: 9.5,
    lineDataSymbol: 'circle', // default for line charts
    lineDataSymbolSize: 8, // default for line charts
    lineDataSymbolLineSize: 0.25, // default for line charts
    lineDataSymbolLineColor: '', // always use the same color for the respective data or value or series or category
    lineSize: 2.25, // default for line charts
    barDir: 'bar', // can be 'bar' or 'col'
    barGrouping: 'stacked', // can be 'clustered' or 'stacked' or 'percentStacked'
    barGapWidthPct: 50, // default for bar charts
    barOverlapPct: -15, // default for bar charts
    dataLabel: { showValue: false }, // never use data labels
    showTitle: 'true', // default for all charts
    title: 'chartTitle',
    titleFontFace: 'Arial',
    titleBold: true,
    titleFontSize: 12,
    titleColor: '000000',
    titlePos: { x: 0, y: 0 }, // default position for title
    catAxisLineShow: true, // strictly true
    catAxisLineColor: 'A6A6A6',
    catAxisLineWidth: 0.75,
    valAxisLineShow: false, // strictly false
    catAxisLabelFontFace: 'Arial',
    catAxisLabelFontSize: 9.5, // default for all charts
    valAxisMinVal: 0 // default value is zero unless there are negative values
    valGridLine: { color: 'D9D9D9', style: 'solid', size: 0.75 }, // default for all charts
    catGridLine: { style: 'none' }, // strictly none
    serGridLine: { style: 'none' }, // strictly none
    catAxisMajorTickMark: 'none', // strictly none
    catAxisMinorTickMark: 'none' // strictly none
};


// 4. CHART ADDITION
slide<slideNumber>.addChart(pptx.ChartType.[TYPE], chartData, chartOptions);


#### 2. ALLOWED CHART TYPES ONLY
- `pptx.ChartType.bar`
- `pptx.ChartType.line`
- `pptx.ChartType.pie`
- `pptx.ChartType.area`
- **FORBIDDEN**: All other chart types


#### 3. MANDATORY S&P COLOR PALETTES: colors must be used in this order:

    '006D89',  // Ocean 7
    'DC7900',  // Gold 7B  
    'B92051',  // Magenta 7
    '501555',  // Purple 9
    '0F9E7A',  // Teal 7
    '00495B',  // Ocean 9
    'C94100',  // Orange 7
    '1D3BAA',  // Blue 8
    'CD6083',  // Magenta 5
    '125E1F',  // Green 9
    '929497',  // Grey 7
    '782080',  // Purple 7
    '7284CA',  // Blue 5
    '9D5700',  // Gold 9
    'B280B6',  // Purple 4
    '566CBF',  // Blue 6
    '6CABBB',  // Ocean 4
    'C18B28',  // Ochre 7
    '3C9D4D',  // Green 6
    '6B0F01'  // Maroon 9

#### 4. ADJUSTABLE CHART POSITIONING

// CHART DIMENSIONS (modify as needed)
const chartPosition = {
    x: <x>,    // Left margin (adjustable)
    y: <y>,    // Top margin (adjustable)
    w: <w>,      // Width (adjustable)
    h: <h>       // Height (adjustable)

##### 5. UNITS IN TITLES

- Example: `"Revenue Growth (%)"`

>step_generateSlide:prompt:model=Claude Sonnet 4 v1;temperature=0;max_tokens=32000
##system_prompt:
Generate the slide code using the given template and data.

**CRITICAL RULES FOR SUSTAINABLE1:**
1. If ${step_division_output} === "sustainable1": You are not allowed to pass `slide<slideNumber>.addText(\"[Report type]\", { placeholder: \"reportType\" });` or add any text such as 'INSIGHT', 'STRATEGIC REPORT', 'MARKET BRIEFING', 'DATA', 'HEADLINE ANALYSIS'
2. If there is an addText function with `{ placeholder: \"reportType\" }`, you must remove this line of code.

**CRITICAL RULES FOR FOOTNOTES:**
1. Check that the same urls from ${step_extractUrls_output} comes from ${user_input}
2. NEVER include the URLs that start with https://snp-mediaportal.qbank.se/assets/deployedFiles/
3. When you see existing footnote text, APPEND the URLs to it using this format:
    - Keep the original footnote text exactly as it is
    - Do NOT replace or remove any existing footnote content
    - Footnotes must start with "Sources: " and end with a period
    - If ${step_documentRead_output} is used in slide creation, you MUST add all the names of the source documents to the footnote section of each slide.
    - Add " | Document sources: " followed by the source documents in the footnotes of each slide.
    - NEVER create or guess website names, domains or links. Do NOT guess or assume any URL format.
    - Every URL in the footnotes must match those given in ${step_extractUrls_output}
    - Every source document in the footnotes must match those from ${step_documentRead_output}
    - These rules NEVER apply to the title slide (slide 1).

**Examples:**
Without URLs: "Source: S&P Global"
With URLs: "Source: S&P Global | Web sources: https://example1.com, https://example2.com | Document sources: example1.docx, example 2.pptx"

This enhancement is MANDATORY for all slides - preserve original footnote content and add URLs.

**CRITICAL RULES FOR IMAGES:**
1. When the template code contains an image placeholder like '[imageUrl]', you MUST ALWAYS replace it with the URL provided in the `${step_imageSelect_output}`.
2. You are NOT ALLOWED to use the descriptive text from the slide data (`${step_slidePlan_output}`) for any `path` property in an `addImage` function.
3. DO NOT guess, assume or change any character in the URL.

**Example 1:**
- Slide Data says: "imageUrl": "A picture of a sunset."
- Image Select output is: "https://.../sunset.png"
- Your code MUST use 'https://.../sunset.png' for the path.

**Example 2:**
- Slide Data says: "use logo": "redblack"
- Your code MUST use 'https://snp-mediaportal.qbank.se/assets/deployedFiles/....png' for the path.

Replace all placeholders (-add ...-) with actual content from the slide data.
Check that every URL for addImages must match those given in ${step_imageSelect_output}
Ensure all text is properly escaped for JavaScript.
Return only the JavaScript code, no markdown blocks or explanations.

**IMAGE OUTPUT:**
${step_imageSelect_output}

**CRITICAL RULE FOR CHARTS:**
- Strictly follow the instructions and settings in ${step_chartInstructions_output}

${step_chartPrompt_output}

you generate JavaScript that uses pptxgenjs. Your code must never produce invalid JS strings, out-of-bounds shapes, undefined styles, or missing masters. Follow these rules exactly.

make sure each slide tells a story. make the presentation visually appealing to hold attention of the audience. !!! IMPORTANT: !!! NEVER change the x, y, w and h values in the code unless you are explicitly told to do so.

String & Notes Safety
- Use template literals (backticks) for any multi-sentence text or notes: addText(\...`), addNotes(`...`)`.
- Do not use single ' or double " quotes for long strings. If a backtick is needed inside content, escape it as ```.
- Output actual newlines in template literals (don‚Äôt write \n unless you mean a literal backslash+n).
- Normalize punctuation to plain ASCII where possible. If you emit curly quotes or em dashes, keep them inside template literals only.
- Never include unescaped control characters. Strip ASCII < 0x20 except tab, CR, LF.
- Do not use markdown formatting. It will not show in PowerPoint. Never use **text** to highlight text
- Double check text objects to make sure quotes are correctly opened and closed. Be particularly aware of nested quotes in text blocs.
- NEVER do this for slide number placeholders: slide4.addText('[slide number]'...

double check that there are no unclosed strings. avoid special characters in strings that would cause issues. Example, this will cause the code not to render:
"""slide_1.addText('The Genesis of a Transformation: Thomson Reuters\\' Strategic Shift', { x: 0.62, y: 2.14, w: 7.86, h: 1.53, fontSize: 44, color: colors.white, bold: true, fontFace: 'Arial', valign: 'bottom'});"""

if an apostrophe <'> is in the text then wrap the text in <`> to avoid this error.

double check that you have delivered the complete code. incomplete code will cause the final powerpoint not to render.

Make sure to return the image urls exactly as given to you. do not change case (upper or lower case characters). Never invent, assume or reinterpret missing details in the urls.

DOUBLE CHECK ALL OF THIS OR YOU CODE WILL BREAK!!!

>>When constructing PowerPoint slides using pptxgenjs, carefully review all text and content before passing it to the slide.

>>Do not include smart quotes, em-dashes, or other non-standard Unicode characters; replace them with standard ASCII equivalents (e.g., straight quotes, hyphens).
Remove or replace any unsupported formatting, symbols, or excessive newline characters, especially in speaker notes and text boxes.
Ensure all text is compatible with XML serialization to prevent file corruption or repair errors in PowerPoint.
Validate that all content passed to pptxgenjs methods will render correctly and not cause errors or require PowerPoint to repair the file.

>>When generating code for multiple slides or sequential code blocks, always append a unique suffix (such as _slide1, _slide2, etc.) to every variable name you create for each slide. This includes constants, arrays, and any other identifiers. Do not reuse variable names across slides. This ensures all variables are unique and prevents redeclaration errors.

!!!Correct Structure (MANDATORY)
!!!You must always generate code that follows this exact pattern:

>>!!!NEVER wrap your response in code ```  !!! YOU ARE NOT ALLOWED DO THIS: ```javascript

make sure to use ${step_slideLoop_output} to name the slide ... in this part:

let slide<slideNumber> = 

Always add logos last so that they appear on top of other elements.

step_assembleHTML:data
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
${step_head_output}
</head>
<body>
<div class="container">
    <hr>
    <h1>S&P Global PowerPoint Generator</h1>
    <hr>
    <img src="${step_agentImage_output}" alt = "EDP" class = "header-image" style="width:190px; height:87px; object-fit:contain;">
    <br><hr>
    <button onclick="generatePPT()">Click to Download Your PowerPoint</button>
    <div class="status" id="status"></div>
</div>
<script>
function updateStatus(message) {
    document.getElementById('status').textContent = message;
}

function generatePPT() {
    try {
        updateStatus('Generating presentation...');
        
        ${step_pptxInit_output}
        
        ${step_sustainable1Layouts_output}
        ${step_otherLayouts_output}
        ${step_disclaimerLayout_output}

        ${step_accumulateSlides_output}

        ${step_contactUsSlide_output}
        ${step_bestPracticesSlide_output}
        ${step_resourcesSlide_output}
        ${step_finalDisclaimerSlide_output}
        ${step_finalDisclaimerSlide2_output}
                
        updateStatus('Downloading...');
        pptx.writeFile({ fileName: "presentation.pptx" })
            .then(() => updateStatus('Download complete!'))
            .catch(err => updateStatus('Error: ' + err.message));
    } catch (error) {
        updateStatus('Error: ' + error.message);
        console.error(error);
    }
}
</script>
</body>
</html>
----
step_download:download:file_type=html;file_name=
${step_assembleHTML_output}
----

</ol>
